Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — Singleton
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — Transient
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — Transient
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps config consistent app-wide. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation creates fresh state — no stale data carried over between visits to a page. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the ViewModel lifetime. A new page + new ViewModel per navigation avoids UI state bugs. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless or intentionally shared services (HTTP clients, caches, loggers).
- **Transient** — anything tied to a screen visit (pages, ViewModels).
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET). Avoid unless you create your own `IServiceScope`.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **Transient** or **Scoped** service into a **Singleton** — it effectively becomes a singleton too, which can cause stale-state bugs.
